The corporation should issue debt to fully finance the project and maintain a 70/30 capital structure to maximize Stephenson's equity per share. Kim Weyand's study demonstrates that the company's cost of capital is 12.5 percent, more than the 8 percent bond coupon rate. The corporation can improve earnings and stock price by issuing debt due to lower borrowing costs. A 70/30 capital structure balances financial distress risk with earnings potential. Higher debt increases financial crisis risk and lowers bond ratings and coupon rates. Finally, by issuing debt and retaining a 70/30 capital structure, the corporation can use the corporate tax rate to boost earnings and stock price. 